    <h2>1. Why Minimal Planning Works</h2>

    <p>
      A minimal planner reduces visual noise.  
      This has three powerful effects:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Less anxiety:</strong> the page doesn‚Äôt shout at you.</li>
      <li><strong>More focus:</strong> your attention lands on what truly matters.</li>
      <li><strong>Better consistency:</strong> because it feels easy to return to every day.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Many people think productivity means doing more.  
      Minimal planning teaches you that productivity actually means **doing less ‚Äî but better**.
    </p>

    <!-- SECTION 2 -->
    <h2>2. The Core Principle: One Page, One Goal</h2>

    <div class="minimal-box">
      üéØ **Minimal Planning Rule:**  
      You don‚Äôt write everything.  
      You write only what matters today.
    </div>

    <p>
      This tiny shift changes everything.  
      Your planner becomes a tool you trust ‚Äî not a reminder of what you didn‚Äôt do.
    </p>

    <!-- SECTION 3 -->
    <h2>3. What a Minimal Daily Page Should Include</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Top 3 priorities</strong> ‚Äî the only tasks that truly matter</li>
      <li><strong>Short to-do list</strong> ‚Äî maximum of 5 items</li>
      <li><strong>Notes or reminders</strong> ‚Äî one small space</li>
      <li><strong>Reflection or gratitude</strong> ‚Äî one line</li>
      <li><strong>Water / health tracker</strong> ‚Äî simple, not decorated</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      That‚Äôs it.  
      No overload. No clutter. No stress.
    </p>

